169 qualified donation was or is planned to be spent.
170 (2) A schedule of payments made to any person during
171 the preceding tax year for the purpose of soliciting or
172 managing the qualified donations received.
173 (d) An eligible entity shall report all donations
174 received from a taxpayer to the department within 30 days of
175 the receipt of that donation.
176 Section 7. Annually, the board and the department shall
177 jointly prepare a report that, at a minimum, includes all
178 qualified donations reported by eligible entities and all tax
179 credits claimed and approved pursuant to this act for the
180 preceding tax year. This report shall be provided to the
181 Legislature by the fifth day of the next regular session.
182 Section 8. (a) A taxpayer may claim a tax credit to
183 offset eligible taxes for each qualified donation as provided
184 in this section. The tax credit shall be provided as follows:
185 (1) For a qualified donor who is a single individual, a
186 head of household, or married, filing a separate return, an
187 amount equal to 100 percent of the qualified donations to the
188 taxpayer made during the tax year for which the credit is
189 claimed, not to exceed fifteen thousand dollars ($15,000).
190 (2) For a qualified donor who is married, filing a
191 joint return, 100 percent of the qualified donations to the
192 taxpayer made during the tax year for which the credit is
193 claimed, not to exceed thirty thousand dollars ($30,000).
194 (3)a. For a qualified donor that is taxed as a
195 pass-through entity under subchapters S or K of the Internal
196 Revenue Code, a limited liability company, or a professional
Page 7

Revenue Code, a limited liability company, or a professional
SB111 INTRODUCED
197 corporation, 100 percent of the qualified donations to the
198 taxpayer made during the tax year for which the credit is
199 claimed, not to exceed four hundred fifty thousand dollars
200 ($450,000).
201 b. The tax credit shall be taken by the taxpayer on a
202 pro rata basis according to an individual's percentage of
203 ownership in the entity or fifteen thousand dollars ($15,000),
204 whichever is less. In the case of a qualified donor that is
205 taxed as a corporation under the Internal Revenue Code, an
206 amount equal to 100 percent or 75 percent of the corporation's
207 income, excise, utility, or insurance premium tax, not to
208 exceed the amount of the corporation's income, excise,
209 utility, or insurance premium tax liability, whichever is
210 less, with a contribution limit each tax year of five hundred
211 thousand dollars ($500,000).
212 (b)(1) The total amount of the tax credit for a tax
213 year may not exceed the taxpayer's tax liability or, for
214 financial institutions, the state portion of the taxpayer's
215 financial institution excise tax liability.
216 (2) Any unused tax credit may be carried forward for up
217 to three years following the qualified donations but shall not
218 be transferable.
219 (c)(1) The tax credits may be claimed beginning January
220 1, 2027, for the 2027 tax year.
221 (2) Except as provided in subdivision (b)(2), no tax
222 credit may be claimed after tax year 2031.
223 (d)(1) The statewide annual aggregate of the tax credit
224 allowed for qualified donations shall not exceed twenty-five
